Just some small talk
to get us started.

00:00:30.700 --> 00:00:32.980
I promise to tell you the
stories about contamination

00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:34.800
and unintentional contamination.

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:40.710
Before we dive in,
what a life, right?

00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:42.320
Steve Jobs.

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:44.800
That was really something.

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:47.210
Moments like that, I think
the best you can possibly do

00:00:47.210 --> 00:00:49.900
is to celebrate the person.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:53.570
And well, in honor
of his inventiveness

00:00:53.570 --> 00:00:56.440
and the way he really
turned Apple around,

00:00:56.440 --> 00:01:00.740
I just wanted to focus
a minute on that.

00:01:00.740 --> 00:01:03.490
Speaking of contamination and
unintentional contamination,

00:01:03.490 --> 00:01:08.200
the effect on processing,
the history books

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:10.130
are full of this
folklore, if you

00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:12.100
start talking to people
who grow crystals

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:15.310
and who manufacture solar cells.

00:01:15.310 --> 00:01:18.140
The growth of the crystals
that are used to actually make

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:21.060
the wafers that ultimately
wind up being solar cells

00:01:21.060 --> 00:01:23.550
is a little bit of
a-- how would you

00:01:23.550 --> 00:01:26.940
say-- a little bit of an art.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:29.320
It is being codified
rather well now.

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:31.630
And there's some strong
science behind it.

00:01:31.630 --> 00:01:36.419
But by and large,
up to very recently,

00:01:36.419 --> 00:01:37.960
it was more of an
art than a science.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.750
The best crystal growers are
people who are very observant

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:48.180
it and who are able to look
out and see correlations

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:51.470
where they weren't
immediately visible to others.

00:01:51.470 --> 00:01:54.850
So in one particular
factory, they

00:01:54.850 --> 00:01:57.600
started noticing that they had
yield losses during the winter

00:01:57.600 --> 00:01:58.380
time.

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:00.690
And in particular they
had extreme yield losses

00:02:00.690 --> 00:02:02.910
whenever there was
a big snowstorm.

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:06.830
And it was somebody, one of
the shift leads, I believe,

00:02:06.830 --> 00:02:09.240
who traced it back
to the salt that

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:11.170
was marching in
on people's boots

00:02:11.170 --> 00:02:12.760
as they were coming
into the factory.

00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:16.180
And that sodium was
contaminating the silicon melt

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:19.670
and resulting in the poor
quality of the crystals that

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:20.880
were being grown.

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:24.020
Flash forward several years
at Fraunhofer Institute

00:02:24.020 --> 00:02:26.680
for Solar Energy Systems
in Freiburg, Germany

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:31.360
where the observant cell
manufacture started noticing,

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:34.760
well, gee, our efficiencies
are always lower on Fridays.

00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:35.830
Why is that?

00:02:35.830 --> 00:02:39.470
And eventually, they traced
the problem down to the fact

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:41.700
that, on Fridays,
the technicians

00:02:41.700 --> 00:02:43.630
would go out to lunch
at a Chinese restaurant.

00:02:43.630 --> 00:02:46.490
And they would come back, and
their breath and their hands

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:48.330
would be MSG.

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:50.960
And that was, again,
the sodium was downing

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:52.670
performance of the devices.

00:02:52.670 --> 00:02:54.080
As so it's really interesting.

00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:57.640
This kind of sounds like
something you might see in a TV

00:02:57.640 --> 00:03:01.990
show where that scientist in
the lab coat waltzes into a room

00:03:01.990 --> 00:03:03.910
and says, it must be the sodium.

00:03:03.910 --> 00:03:04.410
Right?

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:05.330
And then they test it.

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:06.370
And oh, my gosh,
it's the sodium.

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:07.885
Now, problem solving
the real world

00:03:07.885 --> 00:03:09.135
doesn't quite happen that way.

00:03:09.135 --> 00:03:11.650
It involves a very
methodical approach

00:03:11.650 --> 00:03:14.670
to testing a variety
of hypotheses,

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:16.690
first brainstorming in
a structured manner,

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:18.430
identifying the most
likely candidates,

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:21.010
and going about
solving the problem,

00:03:21.010 --> 00:03:22.940
performing a series
of design experiments

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:26.140
to really get to the root cause.

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:28.340
So it's an interesting story.

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:29.770
It's an interesting aside.

00:03:29.770 --> 00:03:32.620
Solving contamination problems,
though, is very difficult.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:34.340
And the best thing
you can possibly

00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:36.460
do if you're growing
crystals is to keep

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:39.770
your system more clean than
you think you need it to be.

00:03:39.770 --> 00:03:41.830
That's the best
advice I can give.

00:03:41.830 --> 00:03:44.390
I was just talking with some
folks in Caltech the other day.

00:03:44.390 --> 00:03:46.260
They were running into
contamination issues.

00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:50.320
And that advice goes a long way.

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:50.820
OK.

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:53.620
Well, let's go ahead and get
started in the topic today.

00:03:53.620 --> 00:03:59.030
Back from Phoenix and eyes are
red from irritation of having

00:03:59.030 --> 00:04:00.630
been awake for too many hours.

00:04:00.630 --> 00:04:02.240
So that could only
mean one thing.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:04.047
Contacts, right?

00:04:04.047 --> 00:04:06.130
So we're going to be talking
about contacts today,

00:04:06.130 --> 00:04:09.560
charge extraction, as well.

00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:12.940
And to situate us
on the roadmap,

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:15.040
we have our
fundamentals right here.

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:17.600
We're about to jump forward
into the technology, which

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:18.839
is really exciting.

00:04:18.839 --> 00:04:20.709
We're about out of
the woods here, folks.

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:22.610
And finally, into the
cross-cutting themes.

00:04:22.610 --> 00:04:25.370
And so, again, every
photovoltaic device

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:28.346
must obey this general
equation right here

00:04:28.346 --> 00:04:30.220
where the output energy
over the input energy

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:31.910
equals a conversion efficiency.

00:04:31.910 --> 00:04:34.770
And for most solar cells, this
is represented by this right

00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:35.270
here.

00:04:35.270 --> 00:04:39.550
And we have now tackled every
single one of those, at least

00:04:39.550 --> 00:04:42.290
in a very fundamental way.

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:45.510
And now, finally, we are focused
on the output, the charge

00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:49.510
collection, in other words,
the contacting of the device.

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:51.257
Again, the total
cell efficiency is

00:04:51.257 --> 00:04:53.590
going to be the product of
each of these individual cell

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:55.470
efficiencies here.

00:04:55.470 --> 00:04:59.150
And contacts are a
very, very easy way

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:02.180
to kill your device
in a variety of ways.

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:04.900
And we'll get to some of
these points right here.

00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:06.970
As a matter of
fact, this s back,

00:05:06.970 --> 00:05:08.820
this surface
recombination velocity

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:10.390
on the backside
of the device, is

00:05:10.390 --> 00:05:12.347
a contact-related phenomenon.

00:05:12.347 --> 00:05:14.430
And that's exactly where
the water is spilling out

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:17.540
of this bucket right here.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:19.490
Learning objectives.

00:05:19.490 --> 00:05:21.920
The idea is to start
out with describing

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:25.750
the purpose of contacts,
and their most common types,

00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:28.526
then to describe the impact
of good and poor contacts

00:05:28.526 --> 00:05:30.150
on I-V characteristics,
in other words,

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:32.457
to describe the device
impact of contacts.

00:05:32.457 --> 00:05:34.040
So we're convinced
that this is really

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:36.582
something we should be spending
a lot of time thinking about.

00:05:36.582 --> 00:05:39.164
Then we're going to sketch the
I-V characteristics of Schottky

00:05:39.164 --> 00:05:40.100
and Ohmic contacts.

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:42.640
We'll learn what those mean.

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:44.180
I hope you know
what ohmic means.

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:47.410
Describe what fundamental
material parameters determine

00:05:47.410 --> 00:05:50.430
I-V characteristics of a
contact/semiconductor junction,

00:05:50.430 --> 00:05:53.390
sketch common band alignments,
and sketch common solar cell

00:05:53.390 --> 00:05:55.067
device architectures,
once we're done.

00:05:55.067 --> 00:05:57.400
And then we can look back and
gaze over the fundamentals

00:05:57.400 --> 00:06:00.620
and say, Ha, ha,
how far we've come.

00:06:00.620 --> 00:06:02.880
And now that you look
at a solar cell device,

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:05.240
hopefully, you'll look at it
in a much more profound way

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:07.840
than you did in the
first day of class.

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:10.110
The more you know,
the more you see.

00:06:10.110 --> 00:06:11.840
So contacts, why
do we need them?

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:13.909
We need to extract the
carriers from the device.

00:06:13.909 --> 00:06:15.950
We need to prevent the
back-diffusion of carriers

00:06:15.950 --> 00:06:18.817
into the device.

00:06:18.817 --> 00:06:21.400
These contacts, in general, have
been studied very extensively

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:22.810
in the semiconductor industry.

00:06:22.810 --> 00:06:25.072
Why is that?

00:06:25.072 --> 00:06:27.280
Why do we need contacts in
the semiconductor industry

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:30.850
to make integrated circuits?

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:31.990
Obvious answer.

00:06:31.990 --> 00:06:32.822
We need wires.

00:06:32.822 --> 00:06:35.280
We need to extract the charges
from our transistors, right?

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:38.080
So we're injecting charge,
pulling out charge.

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:40.380
So contacts have been
pretty extensively studied

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:41.630
in the semiconductor industry.

00:06:41.630 --> 00:06:43.620
And we're going to
leverage that a lot.

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:46.740
We're not going to reinvent the
wheel where we don't need to.

00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:49.290
Contacts are
semiconductor-specific.

00:06:49.290 --> 00:06:53.380
Fundamentals apply
broadly, but the specifics

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:56.600
pertain to-- or the devil's in
the details, in other words.

00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:59.170
So there are very
specific effects

00:06:59.170 --> 00:07:03.420
that occur, depending on the
precise semiconductor metal

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:04.890
combination.

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:09.050
And lastly, the
contacts are heavily

00:07:09.050 --> 00:07:11.590
influenced by the interface
between the semiconductor

00:07:11.590 --> 00:07:12.780
and the metal.

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:15.490
We're going to be talking
about that as well.

00:07:15.490 --> 00:07:18.450
So typical materials
used for contacts

00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:22.620
include metals, transparent
conducting oxides.

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:26.040
And also, we can find heavily
doped organic materials

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:28.390
as well.

00:07:28.390 --> 00:07:29.360
Metals, we understand.

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:32.440
OK, they're optically opaque
and electrically conductive.

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:34.770
That means they conduct
electricity very nicely.

00:07:34.770 --> 00:07:36.900
And so our series resistance
along the metal wire

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:37.775
should be low.

00:07:37.775 --> 00:07:39.650
But they're optically
opaque, meaning they're

00:07:39.650 --> 00:07:41.150
resulting in a shading loss.

00:07:41.150 --> 00:07:43.004
So if we cover entire
front side with metal,

00:07:43.004 --> 00:07:45.170
we're not going to have a
very efficient solar cell,

00:07:45.170 --> 00:07:48.330
because our absorption of
light is going to be very poor.

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:50.960
On the other hand,
transparent conducting oxides

00:07:50.960 --> 00:07:53.800
are optically transparent and
electrically conductive, not

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:56.910
quite as conductive as
metals, but pretty close.

00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:59.990
So let me think about
that for a minute.

00:07:59.990 --> 00:08:03.570
A material that is
optically transparent--

00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:06.410
that means it must have
a very large band gap

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:08.600
to let the light through,
does interact with it,

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:10.170
but is electrically conductive.

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:13.440
In other words, it has a high
concentration of free carriers

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:16.030
that can move around the
material and conduct charge.

00:08:16.030 --> 00:08:18.562
How is that possible?

00:08:18.562 --> 00:08:20.020
I hope you're asking
that question,

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:22.810
because this perplexed me
for a long time as well.

00:08:22.810 --> 00:08:25.250
And we'll answer that
in a couple of slides.

00:08:25.250 --> 00:08:27.970
First, the properties of TCOs.

00:08:27.970 --> 00:08:31.080
What makes a transparent
conducting oxide a transparent

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:31.980
conducting oxide?

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:34.355
I figure I'll spend a couple
slides on this, since metals

00:08:34.355 --> 00:08:35.570
are pretty self-evident.

00:08:35.570 --> 00:08:37.240
But TCOs, this might
be the first time

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:38.409
you're encountering them.

00:08:38.409 --> 00:08:41.020
They're present in a
variety of devices.

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:44.230
If you have an iPhone,
or if you've ever

00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:49.140
seen certain types of military
aircraft, TCOs are involved.

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:51.920
So the material is
very transparent.

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:55.300
You can see the transparency
over quite a broad wavelength

00:08:55.300 --> 00:09:01.160
range here, cutting off only
in the several eV range here.

00:09:01.160 --> 00:09:03.150
Transparency begins to
drop, because you're

00:09:03.150 --> 00:09:05.510
able to excite carries
across the band gap.

00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:07.280
So it's a very large
band gap material,

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:10.100
and yet, the conductivity
is very good.

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:13.980
So here, we can see that the
conductivity of ITO, that's

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:17.420
indium tin oxide, that's a
particular type of transparent

00:09:17.420 --> 00:09:19.720
conducting oxide, is
almost as good as silver.

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:21.900
Not quite, but it's
approaching it.

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:26.770
And so again, the conductivity,
which is 1 over the resistivity

00:09:26.770 --> 00:09:29.400
is related to the carrier
concentration and the mobility,

00:09:29.400 --> 00:09:30.880
as we've seen before.

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:34.450
And therefore, there must
be a lot of free carriers.

00:09:34.450 --> 00:09:38.210
And they must be fairly mobile,
to move around the material.

00:09:38.210 --> 00:09:40.130
So how does that work?

00:09:40.130 --> 00:09:43.350
Band gap greater than 3.1
eV, transmittance very high,

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:46.760
as a result, but still a
large number of carriers.

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:49.930
Well, if we consider our
band gap right here--

00:09:49.930 --> 00:09:52.270
and we'll consider floating
Fermi energy right now,

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:54.600
we'll explain why that's
pegged there in a minute--

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:58.099
we assume that the
band gap is very large,

00:09:58.099 --> 00:10:00.640
so that light can go through,
and it's optically transparent.

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:04.280
But now, by doping the material
with a specific type of dopant

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:07.150
that forms mid-gap
states, we're going

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:12.350
to create a new energy level
here that is partially filled.

00:10:12.350 --> 00:10:16.090
We can then excite, with
relatively little energy,

00:10:16.090 --> 00:10:19.850
carriers into the excited
states within that orange band,

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:22.705
and they can transport charge
throughout the material.

00:10:22.705 --> 00:10:24.830
On the other hand, if we
come in with a high energy

00:10:24.830 --> 00:10:27.580
photon or a moderate
energy photo,

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:29.240
let's say, in the
visible, it doesn't

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:32.520
have quite enough energy to
excite from that orange band

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:35.060
into the conduction band,
nor from the valence band

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:37.760
into the orange band, the
intermediate band there.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:40.960
And that's the general principle
of how transparent conducting

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:43.210
oxides function.

00:10:43.210 --> 00:10:46.930
You can have indium doped
tin oxide, for instance, ITO,

00:10:46.930 --> 00:10:48.920
as a classic example.

00:10:48.920 --> 00:10:51.440
And this is the basic premise.

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:54.570
Any questions so far, because
this is kind of important,

00:10:54.570 --> 00:10:56.920
before we launch into-- yeah.

00:10:56.920 --> 00:10:59.552
AUDIENCE: So how big
are those, that E1, E2?

00:10:59.552 --> 00:11:00.510
TONIO BUONASSISI: Yeah.

00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:07.630
So this E3 right here is around
0.4 eV, for a typical TCO.

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:10.660
And E1 and E2, the
sum of both of them

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:13.360
could be on the order
of three to four eV.

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:15.020
Maybe higher.

00:11:15.020 --> 00:11:15.770
Well actually, no.

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:16.842
Sorry.

00:11:16.842 --> 00:11:18.300
Just one of these
transitions right

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:21.740
here could be on the
order of three eV.

00:11:21.740 --> 00:11:24.160
So the entire band gap
could be quite large.

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:26.770
If you think of metal
oxides-- most metal oxides

00:11:26.770 --> 00:11:28.660
have very large band gaps.

00:11:28.660 --> 00:11:32.610
And most TCOs fall
into that category.

00:11:32.610 --> 00:11:35.120
They could be tin
oxide or zinc oxide,

00:11:35.120 --> 00:11:37.960
but heavily doped
with an element,

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:40.620
like indium, or
fluorine, or aluminum,

00:11:40.620 --> 00:11:43.010
to provide that
intermediate band.

00:11:43.010 --> 00:11:45.570
AUDIENCE: What are the doping
concentrations required

00:11:45.570 --> 00:11:46.504
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:11:46.504 --> 00:11:47.420
TONIO BUONASSISI: Yes.

00:11:47.420 --> 00:11:51.530
So this is a deep dive,
and I'm happy to entertain

00:11:51.530 --> 00:11:53.185
that question.

00:11:53.185 --> 00:11:55.060
For those who it kind
of goes over your head,

00:11:55.060 --> 00:11:55.560
don't worry about it.

00:11:55.560 --> 00:11:57.530
We'll return, so plant
a flag post in your mind

00:11:57.530 --> 00:11:58.850
where we're at.

00:11:58.850 --> 00:12:01.734
Remember the hydrogenic donor
model for a dopant atom.

00:12:01.734 --> 00:12:03.150
You introduce it
into the lattice.

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:05.430
And that loosely bound
electron is there, kind of

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:06.710
like a hydrogenic donor.

00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:08.310
It has a certain radius.

00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:10.710
And if you begin doping at
a very high concentration,

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:13.001
those electrons will begin
interfering with each other.

00:12:13.001 --> 00:12:14.410
They'll begin interacting.

00:12:14.410 --> 00:12:17.300
And so instead of forming
one isolated defect level,

00:12:17.300 --> 00:12:19.530
they'll start splitting
and forming a band.

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:21.760
And the density at
which you have to dope

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:24.854
depends on that donor radius.

00:12:24.854 --> 00:12:27.270
So you're typically talking
about concentrations in the 10

00:12:27.270 --> 00:12:31.380
to the 20 per cubic centimeter,
or one atomic percent

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:32.502
or higher.

00:12:32.502 --> 00:12:33.960
So that's the dopant
density that's

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:36.450
required to force
this transition.

00:12:36.450 --> 00:12:38.190
It's pretty cool.

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:40.880
I mean, there are people who
do their PhDs on transparent

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:41.630
conducting oxides.

00:12:41.630 --> 00:12:42.849
Maybe some of you are.

00:12:42.849 --> 00:12:45.140
You could probably come up
and give a lecture about it.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:47.800
So it's a fascinating subject.

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:51.230
And because ITO, or
indium tin oxide,

00:12:51.230 --> 00:12:53.860
is just so amazing in
terms of its conductivity--

00:12:53.860 --> 00:12:55.760
it's almost up there
buttressing again

00:12:55.760 --> 00:13:01.210
silver-- it's very difficult
to replace with something else.

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:04.100
Zinc oxide and its
variants get pretty close,

00:13:04.100 --> 00:13:06.290
like aluminum dope zinc
oxide, sometimes called

00:13:06.290 --> 00:13:07.927
AZO in the PV community.

00:13:07.927 --> 00:13:09.510
They get pretty
close, but they're not

00:13:09.510 --> 00:13:12.580
quite as good in terms
of optical transparency

00:13:12.580 --> 00:13:14.260
and conductivity as ITO.

00:13:14.260 --> 00:13:15.400
Now ITO is a problem.

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:16.610
It contains indium.

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:18.900
And the world supply
of indium is limited.

00:13:18.900 --> 00:13:21.810
It's not the most abundant
element on the Earth's crust.

00:13:21.810 --> 00:13:24.410
If you look at a periodic table,
it's pretty far down there.

00:13:24.410 --> 00:13:26.610
And as you know, the
elemental abundance,

00:13:26.610 --> 00:13:29.590
it has a relative decay
from-- a power law

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:31.570
decay-- from light
elements to heavy elements

00:13:31.570 --> 00:13:33.780
with some fluctuations
in between.

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:36.360
But in general, the star
dust that we have here

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:38.440
is less abundant in
the heavier elements.

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:40.620
And indium is one
of those elements.

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:44.210
And so people are searching
for alternatives to ITO.

00:13:44.210 --> 00:13:47.311
And it's an active area
of research right now.

00:13:47.311 --> 00:13:47.810
OK.

00:13:47.810 --> 00:13:50.970
So for now, let's go
back to the flag post

00:13:50.970 --> 00:13:53.520
that we planted just
a few minutes ago.

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:55.050
For everyone who
didn't quite follow

00:13:55.050 --> 00:13:57.591
the detailed explanation, the
important thing to keep in mind

00:13:57.591 --> 00:14:00.440
is that TCOs are
conductive and transparent.

00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:04.650
And they are so, because of
the unique band structure.

00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:07.410
So we can create contacts
to semiconductors

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:10.520
and extract charge using
either a metal or a TCO.

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:12.890
And right now,
we're going to dive

00:14:12.890 --> 00:14:15.620
into the impact of good
and bad contacts on device

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:16.830
characteristics.

00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:20.064
So during our last-- I believe
it was two lectures ago,

00:14:20.064 --> 00:14:21.980
we talked about the
equivalent circuit diagram

00:14:21.980 --> 00:14:25.500
of a solar cell, this being the
simplest case, now corrected

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:27.640
with our minus 1
term right here.

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:32.380
And we can see our I-V curve in
linear, linear scale and log,

00:14:32.380 --> 00:14:35.220
linear scale there, log
current linear voltage.

00:14:35.220 --> 00:14:36.906
And because this
is an exponential,

00:14:36.906 --> 00:14:38.280
you would expect
a straight line,

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:40.230
and you do see that indeed.

00:14:40.230 --> 00:14:43.365
Now the I-V curve,
in the upper part,

00:14:43.365 --> 00:14:44.990
you can really see
has a very nice fill

00:14:44.990 --> 00:14:47.260
factor as a very sharp kink.

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:48.240
Pops straight up.

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:51.330
And so the fill factor of that
I-V curve, when illuminated,

00:14:51.330 --> 00:14:52.760
will be very high.

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:56.250
And hence, the solar cell
efficiency will be high.

00:14:56.250 --> 00:14:58.880
Not so when you introduce
a series resistance.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:01.540
So when you have that
series resistance component,

00:15:01.540 --> 00:15:04.100
now, at higher
bias voltages, you

00:15:04.100 --> 00:15:06.250
begin to be series
resistance limited,

00:15:06.250 --> 00:15:08.337
which causes the fill
factor to decrease.

00:15:08.337 --> 00:15:10.170
And you can see that
by going back and forth

00:15:10.170 --> 00:15:12.030
between these two slides.

00:15:12.030 --> 00:15:14.570
High fill factor, no
series resistance.

00:15:14.570 --> 00:15:16.907
Lower fill factor,
higher series resistance.

00:15:16.907 --> 00:15:19.490
Especially, if you focus right
here at this point right there,

00:15:19.490 --> 00:15:23.130
you can really see the
decrease of fill factor

00:15:23.130 --> 00:15:25.710
as a result of adding a
series resistance component.

00:15:25.710 --> 00:15:29.332
So contacts, when
improperly performed,

00:15:29.332 --> 00:15:31.790
can add a series resistance
component, a rather significant

00:15:31.790 --> 00:15:34.790
one, and drop the
performance of your device.

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:36.140
Likewise, shunt resistance.

00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:39.730
We saw a simple effect right
here of shunt resistance.

00:15:39.730 --> 00:15:43.050
If the shunt resistance
goes down further

00:15:43.050 --> 00:15:46.990
and the saturation current
goes up even higher,

00:15:46.990 --> 00:15:49.140
it begins to affect the
fill factor as well.

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:53.480
And so shunting can also
be impacted by contacts.

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:56.760
Particularly when you fire your
contacts, in other words when

00:15:56.760 --> 00:16:00.060
you heat your sample up,
or you heat your stack up

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:04.270
to create good contact between
the metal and the semiconductor

00:16:04.270 --> 00:16:07.310
underneath, or the TCO and
the semiconductor underneath,

00:16:07.310 --> 00:16:09.330
a couple of things can happen.

00:16:09.330 --> 00:16:12.430
If you don't get the chemistry
just right at the interface--

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:14.490
maybe didn't clean
your sample properly,

00:16:14.490 --> 00:16:17.570
maybe you didn't heat
it up high enough,

00:16:17.570 --> 00:16:21.960
so that the atoms really started
to interdiffuse and interact--

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:24.880
you can under-fire your contact.

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:27.820
And that results in poor
contact with your semiconductor

00:16:27.820 --> 00:16:30.010
and large series resistance.

00:16:30.010 --> 00:16:32.560
So large series resistance
will, essentially,

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:38.482
impede charge flow and
result in a fill factor loss.

00:16:38.482 --> 00:16:39.940
On the other hand,
if you over-fire

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:42.440
your contact-- let's
say you heat it up,

00:16:42.440 --> 00:16:46.280
but fire it a little too long--
then the contact material

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:48.260
can drive too far into
your semiconductor,

00:16:48.260 --> 00:16:50.160
and you wind up
shunting your device.

00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:51.390
What does a shunt mean?

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:54.360
A shunt mean that the metal
goes straight through the PN

00:16:54.360 --> 00:16:58.710
junction and contacts the base
material on the other side.

00:16:58.710 --> 00:17:00.955
So remember, the PN junction
region of the solar cell

00:17:00.955 --> 00:17:03.530
is only about a micron
away from the surface.

00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:04.930
It's really close.

00:17:04.930 --> 00:17:07.641
So if you have a fast diffusing
metal species and you heat it

00:17:07.641 --> 00:17:09.890
up too much, you get the
metal going straight through,

00:17:09.890 --> 00:17:12.880
in this case, the
n+ layer into the P,

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:14.650
you'll shunt your device.

00:17:14.650 --> 00:17:16.150
So this is the fine
balance that you

00:17:16.150 --> 00:17:18.349
have to walk when
you're putting contact

00:17:18.349 --> 00:17:19.810
metallization on the device.

00:17:19.810 --> 00:17:22.630
You can't over-fire it,
because we wind up with shunts.

00:17:22.630 --> 00:17:24.640
You can't under-fire
it either, because you

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:27.640
might wind up with a very
large contact resistance.

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:31.020
So it's a very tricky
thing to get right.

00:17:31.020 --> 00:17:34.780
We just finished installing a
contact metallization printer

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:35.350
in our lab.

00:17:35.350 --> 00:17:37.560
And Joe, how many
human hours total

00:17:37.560 --> 00:17:41.036
have been spent trying to
optimize the firing process?

00:17:41.036 --> 00:17:43.270
JOE: Probably
about 30 or 40 now?

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:44.990
TONIO BUONASSISI: 30
or 40 human hours?

00:17:44.990 --> 00:17:46.602
So it's still a
work in progress,

00:17:46.602 --> 00:17:48.310
but it takes a while
to really nail that.

00:17:48.310 --> 00:17:49.530
Yes, Ashley?

00:17:49.530 --> 00:17:53.190
ASHLEY: So would
you want your TCO

00:17:53.190 --> 00:17:58.003
to melt at a lower temperature
that your semiconductor?

00:17:58.003 --> 00:18:01.190
Is that another consideration?

00:18:01.190 --> 00:18:03.500
TONIO BUONASSISI: So
let's back up a step.

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:06.010
For the metal case, it's
pretty straightforward.

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:07.610
This is a homogeneous element.

00:18:07.610 --> 00:18:10.750
Let's call it a unary material,
meaning one element comprising

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:12.900
that metal, typically.

00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:16.270
And it's very simple for us
to see, OK, if we keep it up

00:18:16.270 --> 00:18:19.610
and it reacts with our
material, it drives in.

00:18:19.610 --> 00:18:21.590
For a TCO, it's a little
less straightforward,

00:18:21.590 --> 00:18:24.420
because you typically
have a multinary compound,

00:18:24.420 --> 00:18:27.350
meaning several elements
comprising your TCO.

00:18:27.350 --> 00:18:29.060
The formation of this
intermediate band

00:18:29.060 --> 00:18:34.300
right here that forms, really,
the conductivity of the TCO,

00:18:34.300 --> 00:18:36.920
is predicated upon
the principle that you

00:18:36.920 --> 00:18:39.070
have these dopant atoms
homogeneously spaced

00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:40.350
throughout your material.

00:18:40.350 --> 00:18:41.460
If you heat it up
too high and they

00:18:41.460 --> 00:18:42.834
begin to cluster,
in other words,

00:18:42.834 --> 00:18:44.910
precipitate out of
phase, you can wind up

00:18:44.910 --> 00:18:47.970
destroying your TCO, or
increasing the resistivity,

00:18:47.970 --> 00:18:51.690
maybe even decreasing
the optical transparency.

00:18:51.690 --> 00:18:54.440
And so it really is
material-specific

00:18:54.440 --> 00:18:55.815
when we start
talking about TCOs.

00:18:55.815 --> 00:18:57.356
I'd rather not
generalize about them.

00:18:57.356 --> 00:18:58.975
About metals is more
straightforward.

00:18:58.975 --> 00:18:59.474
ASHLEY: OK.

00:18:59.474 --> 00:19:02.286
I guess then, for
metals, you would

00:19:02.286 --> 00:19:07.064
have to choose a metal that
melts before your semiconductor

00:19:07.064 --> 00:19:07.980
melt-- or [INAUDIBLE].

00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:09.896
TONIO BUONASSISI:
Typically, you wouldn't have

00:19:09.896 --> 00:19:12.470
your mental melting, per se.

00:19:12.470 --> 00:19:15.150
What you're looking for is
a chemical reaction here

00:19:15.150 --> 00:19:16.780
at this interface.

00:19:16.780 --> 00:19:20.080
You're looking for
the metal, most often,

00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:23.460
to form a binary compound
between your metal

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:25.490
and the semiconducting
material underneath.

00:19:25.490 --> 00:19:27.889
Let's say you have
nickel and silicon.

00:19:27.889 --> 00:19:29.930
You'd be looking for it
to form a nickel silicide

00:19:29.930 --> 00:19:30.700
at that interface.

00:19:30.700 --> 00:19:31.230
ASHLEY: OK.

00:19:31.230 --> 00:19:31.620
TONIO BUONASSISI:
And that's where

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:33.453
you go to your phase
diagrams and figure out

00:19:33.453 --> 00:19:38.120
what temperature those, say,
intermetallics should form.

00:19:38.120 --> 00:19:40.450
And then you're targeting
that particular temperature

00:19:40.450 --> 00:19:41.600
during your ramp.

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:42.100
ASHLEY: OK.

00:19:42.100 --> 00:19:42.670
TONIO BUONASSISI:
And of course, it's

00:19:42.670 --> 00:19:44.044
not only phase
diagrams which are

00:19:44.044 --> 00:19:47.310
under equilibrium conditions,
kinetics are involved as well.

00:19:47.310 --> 00:19:49.920
So it becomes a
rather tricky process.

00:19:49.920 --> 00:19:51.238
Yeah, question in the back.

00:19:51.238 --> 00:19:53.150
AUDIENCE: This
picture is drawn where

00:19:53.150 --> 00:19:55.580
it says doping is concentrated
underneath [INAUDIBLE].

00:19:55.580 --> 00:19:56.496
TONIO BUONASSISI: Yep.

00:19:56.496 --> 00:19:58.204
AUDIENCE: How do we
manage to concentrate

00:19:58.204 --> 00:20:01.419
the dopant in just that
certain section [INAUDIBLE]?

00:20:01.419 --> 00:20:02.960
TONIO BUONASSISI:
Very good question.

00:20:02.960 --> 00:20:05.457
So we'll explain toward
the end of lecture

00:20:05.457 --> 00:20:07.290
why dopant is concentrated
underneath there.

00:20:07.290 --> 00:20:08.770
For those who are a
little bit more advanced,

00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:11.160
it relates to a tunneling
junction effect or a field

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:12.430
emission effect.

00:20:12.430 --> 00:20:14.740
But we'll explain what
that is for everyone else.

00:20:14.740 --> 00:20:18.880
The way you typically get an
enhanced dopant concentration

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:20.579
right underneath the
metal, first, let's

00:20:20.579 --> 00:20:22.370
appreciate the length
scales involved here.

00:20:22.370 --> 00:20:24.340
The width of that
contact metal is probably

00:20:24.340 --> 00:20:26.920
on the order of
somewhere between,

00:20:26.920 --> 00:20:31.220
let's say, 80 and 120
microns, maybe a little more.

00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:33.590
And so, at those
length scales, we

00:20:33.590 --> 00:20:35.810
don't need photo
lithography to really nail

00:20:35.810 --> 00:20:37.200
a particular location.

00:20:37.200 --> 00:20:39.230
We're not talking about
tens of nanometers.

00:20:39.230 --> 00:20:41.390
It's really something
more macroscopic.

00:20:41.390 --> 00:20:43.660
So we can do it in a few ways.

00:20:43.660 --> 00:20:47.040
On the high end, we could
use an ion implantation tool

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:50.050
to pattern our
material with a mask.

00:20:50.050 --> 00:20:56.970
On the low end, we might diffuse
in the emitter very deeply,

00:20:56.970 --> 00:20:59.900
to create a highly doped
region everywhere, and then

00:20:59.900 --> 00:21:04.420
create a mask using not exactly
a photo lithography process.

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:07.170
It could be a much simpler
contacting process,

00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:09.890
and then etch away some of
the emitter in other regions

00:21:09.890 --> 00:21:14.190
to make it more lightly doped
or, even in silicon's case,

00:21:14.190 --> 00:21:16.700
create a poor silicon
layer and etch that off,

00:21:16.700 --> 00:21:19.000
to distinguish between
the heavily doped

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:20.420
and the lightly doped regions.

00:21:20.420 --> 00:21:23.130
There are a few different
ways to skin that cat.

00:21:23.130 --> 00:21:27.430
And that's one of the beauties
of solar cell processing

00:21:27.430 --> 00:21:29.880
is that it really pertains
to the specific material

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:31.109
system involved.

00:21:31.109 --> 00:21:33.150
But the length scales are
such that you're really

00:21:33.150 --> 00:21:37.900
not typically limited
by photolithography.

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:40.440
You can probably get around
that and use other techniques

00:21:40.440 --> 00:21:41.672
for masking it off.

00:21:41.672 --> 00:21:43.440
Mm-hm.

00:21:43.440 --> 00:21:44.840
Great.

00:21:44.840 --> 00:21:48.710
I see folks are awake today,
despite the P-set due.

00:21:48.710 --> 00:21:52.820
Sketch the I-V characteristics
of Schottky and Ohmic contacts.

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:55.650
OK, so what we're
going to do here

00:21:55.650 --> 00:22:00.885
is talk about how Schottky and
Ohmic contacts come into being.

00:22:00.885 --> 00:22:02.090
And first off, define them.

00:22:02.090 --> 00:22:03.640
So let's define them.

00:22:03.640 --> 00:22:08.530
An Ohmic contact is one in
which I sweep my voltage,

00:22:08.530 --> 00:22:11.650
and I obtain a linear
current response.

00:22:11.650 --> 00:22:13.410
So this is pretty
straightforward.

00:22:13.410 --> 00:22:16.680
It's Ohm's law, follows
Ohm's law, so V equals IR.

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:18.480
This is a linear
relationship then

00:22:18.480 --> 00:22:20.730
between voltage and
current, the slope of which

00:22:20.730 --> 00:22:23.160
is dictated by the resistance.

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:25.490
A Schottky contact,
on the other hand,

00:22:25.490 --> 00:22:28.480
follows this beautiful
exponential curve

00:22:28.480 --> 00:22:31.180
that we've come to know and love
from our ideal diode equation.

00:22:31.180 --> 00:22:33.900
As a matter of fact, it
follows that same expression

00:22:33.900 --> 00:22:34.880
rather nicely.

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:38.110
There's an exponential relation
between voltage and current.

00:22:38.110 --> 00:22:39.994
So whenever we have an
exponential relation

00:22:39.994 --> 00:22:41.660
between voltage and
current, now that we

00:22:41.660 --> 00:22:43.740
know how a PN
junciton works, and we

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:46.430
recall that it's really that
diffusion current that's

00:22:46.430 --> 00:22:50.110
driving the forward
current right here

00:22:50.110 --> 00:22:51.780
under forward bias conditions.

00:22:51.780 --> 00:22:54.710
We've learned that, when
the barrier's too large,

00:22:54.710 --> 00:22:56.700
the electrons just
can't make it over.

00:22:56.700 --> 00:22:58.900
But as a barrier
begins dropping,

00:22:58.900 --> 00:23:01.100
an exponentially increasing
number of electrons

00:23:01.100 --> 00:23:03.630
can jump over that
barrier and move

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:05.662
from the region of
high concentration

00:23:05.662 --> 00:23:07.120
to the region of
low concentration,

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:10.050
or from the n-type material
to the p-type material.

00:23:10.050 --> 00:23:14.250
So when we see an exponential
current voltage response,

00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:17.170
we should immediately think
about some barrier involved

00:23:17.170 --> 00:23:18.460
in our system.

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:22.510
And as we begin
biasing this device--

00:23:22.510 --> 00:23:25.170
in this case, a semiconductor
metal junction--

00:23:25.170 --> 00:23:28.510
as we begin biasing the
semiconductor versus the metal,

00:23:28.510 --> 00:23:32.210
we begin seeing an
exponential current response.

00:23:32.210 --> 00:23:33.680
We should imagine
that there must

00:23:33.680 --> 00:23:37.560
be some barrier in between the
metal and the semiconductor.

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:40.150
And we'll explain how that
barrier comes into being.

00:23:40.150 --> 00:23:43.250
So again, just to recap, making
sure we hit all the points.

00:23:43.250 --> 00:23:44.960
Ohmic, a linear I-V curve.

00:23:44.960 --> 00:23:47.570
And Ohmic contacts
are typically used

00:23:47.570 --> 00:23:49.800
when charge separation
is not the goal

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:51.040
for your metallization.

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:53.380
Let's say you've already
achieved your charge separation

00:23:53.380 --> 00:23:55.160
through the PN junction,
and now, you just

00:23:55.160 --> 00:23:56.576
want to contact
your semiconductor

00:23:56.576 --> 00:23:59.160
to extract the charge,
you'd use an Ohmic contact.

00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:01.100
But you would use
a Schottky contact

00:24:01.100 --> 00:24:05.350
when you want to enforce
some charge separation.

00:24:05.350 --> 00:24:07.320
Typically, not quite
as good as, say,

00:24:07.320 --> 00:24:10.080
a PN junction for
separating charge,

00:24:10.080 --> 00:24:11.780
not quite as high voltage.

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:16.890
But it's a useful tool,
for example, in research.

00:24:16.890 --> 00:24:20.430
So we're going to describe
what fundamental material

00:24:20.430 --> 00:24:23.640
parameters determine the
I-V characteristics of both

00:24:23.640 --> 00:24:27.830
the Ohmic and Schottky
junctions, more generally,

00:24:27.830 --> 00:24:30.650
a contact
semiconductor junction.

00:24:30.650 --> 00:24:34.160
And this dives into
Schottky band theory.

00:24:34.160 --> 00:24:38.240
This is a very idealized
version of the real world.

00:24:38.240 --> 00:24:39.790
It's an idealized
version, because it

00:24:39.790 --> 00:24:42.690
gets us started and points
us in the right direction.

00:24:42.690 --> 00:24:44.630
Then we'll add
layers of complexity,

00:24:44.630 --> 00:24:46.300
until we build up
to really understand

00:24:46.300 --> 00:24:48.050
what's going on inside
of these devices.

00:24:48.050 --> 00:24:48.883
So let's start here.

00:24:48.883 --> 00:24:55.410
This is a very nice, elegant
view of contact theory.

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:56.910
We have our
semiconductor over here.

00:24:56.910 --> 00:24:57.650
Let's walk through this.

00:24:57.650 --> 00:24:59.270
So this is our
energy band diagram.

00:24:59.270 --> 00:25:01.130
We have E on the
vertical axis that

00:25:01.130 --> 00:25:03.260
represents the energy
of the electron,

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:06.250
versus X, some real
space parameter.

00:25:06.250 --> 00:25:07.924
We have our semiconductor
material here.

00:25:07.924 --> 00:25:09.840
We have our valence band,
our conduction band,

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:10.880
and our Fermi energy.

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:14.630
This looks to be an n-type
semiconducting material.

00:25:14.630 --> 00:25:16.950
And we have our vacuum level.

00:25:16.950 --> 00:25:18.700
The vacuum level is
essentially the energy

00:25:18.700 --> 00:25:21.010
at which we remove an electron
from the semiconductor.

00:25:21.010 --> 00:25:24.750
If the semiconductor were
placed, let's say, in a vacuum,

00:25:24.750 --> 00:25:29.700
and we were to excite an
electron out of the material

00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:31.730
through some, let's say,
a photoemission effect,

00:25:31.730 --> 00:25:35.270
we would have to overcome
the energy between the Fermi

00:25:35.270 --> 00:25:36.850
energy and the vacuum level.

00:25:36.850 --> 00:25:40.430
This xi right here is
essentially the electron

00:25:40.430 --> 00:25:42.280
affinity of the semiconductor.

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:46.100
That's the delta in
energy, or q times xi

00:25:46.100 --> 00:25:47.980
is the delta in energy
between the vacuum

00:25:47.980 --> 00:25:49.990
level and the conduction band.

00:25:49.990 --> 00:25:51.740
So we have all of the
variables mapped out

00:25:51.740 --> 00:25:52.820
for the semiconductor.

00:25:52.820 --> 00:25:54.920
Most of them should be
familiar for us already.

00:25:54.920 --> 00:25:58.600
We've added the vacuum
level for completeness.

00:25:58.600 --> 00:26:00.910
The metal, we also
have a Fermi energy,

00:26:00.910 --> 00:26:03.530
we also a chemical
potential of the metal.

00:26:03.530 --> 00:26:07.030
And we have a work function
of the metal, right here.

00:26:07.030 --> 00:26:10.550
So this work function
is defined as the energy

00:26:10.550 --> 00:26:13.850
necessary to remove an
electron from the metal.

00:26:13.850 --> 00:26:17.780
Say again, by if you shined
a light on the material,

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:20.670
it has a high enough energy,
you can begin exciting electrons

00:26:20.670 --> 00:26:25.070
off of the metal with
a photoemission effect.

00:26:25.070 --> 00:26:28.030
And so we have our vacuum levels
in this particular diagram

00:26:28.030 --> 00:26:28.790
lined up.

00:26:28.790 --> 00:26:30.690
And our chemical
potentials are a little bit

00:26:30.690 --> 00:26:33.520
different between the metal
and the semiconductor.

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:37.580
So what do you think will happen
when we put the two together?

00:26:37.580 --> 00:26:39.680
If we put the two together,
the chemical potential

00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:42.570
throughout the entire system
has to be the same, right?

00:26:42.570 --> 00:26:47.136
Because now, they're in good
contact with one another.

00:26:47.136 --> 00:26:48.510
But what about
that vacuum level?

00:26:48.510 --> 00:26:50.070
What's going to happen?

00:26:50.070 --> 00:26:51.820
Will there be
discontinuity, first of all,

00:26:51.820 --> 00:26:53.929
in the vacuum level?

00:26:53.929 --> 00:26:55.970
Can there be a discontinuity
in the vacuum level?

00:26:55.970 --> 00:26:59.670
If I move one little delta
x from the semiconductor

00:26:59.670 --> 00:27:01.350
into the metal,
do I expect there

00:27:01.350 --> 00:27:03.170
to be a discontinuity
in the vacuum level?

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:04.680
No, probably not.

00:27:04.680 --> 00:27:07.930
So there has to be some smooth
change in the vacuum energy,

00:27:07.930 --> 00:27:10.570
relative to the Fermi energy.

00:27:10.570 --> 00:27:12.337
And if the vacuum
level changes, that

00:27:12.337 --> 00:27:14.670
means that the conduction
band and valence band energies

00:27:14.670 --> 00:27:17.800
are also going to change,
relative to the Fermi energy,

00:27:17.800 --> 00:27:20.810
because the valence band
and conduction band energies

00:27:20.810 --> 00:27:25.650
track with the vacuum level--
the vacuum level being defined

00:27:25.650 --> 00:27:27.810
as the amount of energy
necessary to remove

00:27:27.810 --> 00:27:29.220
the electron from the system.

00:27:29.220 --> 00:27:31.470
So what you get when you
put these two materials

00:27:31.470 --> 00:27:34.820
together is something
like this right here.

00:27:34.820 --> 00:27:38.029
This dashed blue line
representing the Fermi energy,

00:27:38.029 --> 00:27:40.320
or the chemical potential
throughout the entire system,

00:27:40.320 --> 00:27:41.870
is the same.

00:27:41.870 --> 00:27:44.690
In this particular case,
we didn't bias our device.

00:27:44.690 --> 00:27:49.600
We're not applying a
battery or some bias voltage

00:27:49.600 --> 00:27:51.500
between one side and the other.

00:27:51.500 --> 00:27:54.750
So we have the same chemical
potential throughout.

00:27:54.750 --> 00:27:56.940
If we have the same chemical
potential throughout,

00:27:56.940 --> 00:27:59.550
notice that we had
to push this up,

00:27:59.550 --> 00:28:01.639
or push the Fermi
energy up, to reach--

00:28:01.639 --> 00:28:04.180
and of course, the work function
in the metal's not changing,

00:28:04.180 --> 00:28:05.990
and so the vacuum
energy also goes up.

00:28:05.990 --> 00:28:08.240
But since there can't be a
discontinuity in the vacuum

00:28:08.240 --> 00:28:11.700
energy, you see a little
bit of a rise of the vacuum

00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:13.290
energy in the semiconductor.

00:28:13.290 --> 00:28:16.430
And of course, the valence band
and conduction bands follow.

00:28:16.430 --> 00:28:18.540
And that results
in this little rise

00:28:18.540 --> 00:28:20.380
right here, right
next to the interface

00:28:20.380 --> 00:28:22.950
between the semiconductor
and the metal.

00:28:22.950 --> 00:28:24.530
Any questions so far?

00:28:24.530 --> 00:28:25.970
AUDIENCE: Is there
a discontinuity

00:28:25.970 --> 00:28:28.370
in the first derivative
of the vacuum level?

00:28:28.370 --> 00:28:29.330
Is there a kink in it?

00:28:29.330 --> 00:28:30.300
TONIO BUONASSISI: Ha.

00:28:30.300 --> 00:28:31.466
A very interesting question.

00:28:31.466 --> 00:28:34.650
So typically, we draw it
as having a discontinuity

00:28:34.650 --> 00:28:35.750
in the first derivative.

00:28:35.750 --> 00:28:37.820
We would draw a very sharp
interface right there.

00:28:37.820 --> 00:28:41.405
But in a practical sense,
I'll reserve judgment

00:28:41.405 --> 00:28:43.780
on that, until I think a little
bit more deeply about it.

00:28:43.780 --> 00:28:46.380
It's difficult for me to
believe that there would be,

00:28:46.380 --> 00:28:49.010
if you zoom in very, very
closely, very finely.

00:28:52.430 --> 00:28:56.050
The bending, let's think
about it from another way,

00:28:56.050 --> 00:28:57.460
from what we already know.

00:28:57.460 --> 00:29:00.060
This is essentially
the second integral

00:29:00.060 --> 00:29:03.450
of the charge distribution
across that interface.

00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:07.310
And if the charge distribution
is sharp enough, sure,

00:29:07.310 --> 00:29:10.870
I suppose you could
get some difference.

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:15.210
But I think-- I'll have
to research judgement,

00:29:15.210 --> 00:29:17.400
but my gut is telling
me that there would not

00:29:17.400 --> 00:29:21.280
be at a very fine
microscopic level.

00:29:21.280 --> 00:29:23.970
In general, though, we draw
it looking much like this.

00:29:26.814 --> 00:29:28.710
OK?

00:29:28.710 --> 00:29:31.740
Any other questions about this,
about how we constructed it,

00:29:31.740 --> 00:29:34.720
using the Anderson method?

00:29:34.720 --> 00:29:35.220
No?

00:29:35.220 --> 00:29:36.090
OK.

00:29:36.090 --> 00:29:37.990
Why don't we continue?

00:29:37.990 --> 00:29:40.804
What we've done
right here is fill

00:29:40.804 --> 00:29:43.220
in those diagrams, the same
ones that you were looking at,

00:29:43.220 --> 00:29:45.410
with many more variables.

00:29:45.410 --> 00:29:48.180
The purpose of this
is to get to the point

00:29:48.180 --> 00:29:52.330
where we can describe
the built-in voltage.

00:29:52.330 --> 00:29:53.840
Remember, we
mentioned that, if we

00:29:53.840 --> 00:29:56.040
have some exponential
current voltage response,

00:29:56.040 --> 00:29:59.140
there should be some barrier
embedded inside of our system.

00:29:59.140 --> 00:30:01.320
And this right here
is that barrier.

00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:05.390
So these series of
variables are teaching us

00:30:05.390 --> 00:30:08.490
how to derive it,
how to discover

00:30:08.490 --> 00:30:10.990
how large that barrier is.

00:30:10.990 --> 00:30:12.700
And this other
component right here,

00:30:12.700 --> 00:30:14.866
which is the width of the
space charge region, which

00:30:14.866 --> 00:30:19.750
is the width of this, so-called,
curved region, if you will,

00:30:19.750 --> 00:30:22.950
is also going to
be of importance.

00:30:22.950 --> 00:30:26.250
So first off, let's
think about it this way.

00:30:26.250 --> 00:30:28.980
If we are looking at this
system from the electron's

00:30:28.980 --> 00:30:31.720
perspective, we have
an n-type semiconductor

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:36.070
right here coming up
against the metal.

00:30:36.070 --> 00:30:38.620
If our work function
of the metal

00:30:38.620 --> 00:30:40.870
is larger than the
work function--

00:30:40.870 --> 00:30:44.170
or the so-called work
function of the semiconductor,

00:30:44.170 --> 00:30:46.282
which is really the
electron affinity

00:30:46.282 --> 00:30:48.240
plus the delta in energy
between the conduction

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:49.660
band of the Fermi energy.

00:30:49.660 --> 00:30:52.300
But if the work function of
the metal is larger than that,

00:30:52.300 --> 00:30:55.430
we can see that the electrons
should very easily plop down

00:30:55.430 --> 00:30:56.650
into the metal.

00:30:56.650 --> 00:31:00.774
And there shouldn't be-- let's
see, in that particular case,

00:31:00.774 --> 00:31:02.190
work function of
the mental should

00:31:02.190 --> 00:31:05.360
result in an Ohmic contact
for the minority carriers,

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:06.550
in that case.

00:31:06.550 --> 00:31:09.150
But in terms of
the barrier height,

00:31:09.150 --> 00:31:11.690
this barrier height right
here would be determined

00:31:11.690 --> 00:31:14.830
by that equation there.

00:31:14.830 --> 00:31:19.280
The contact potential,
the built-in bias voltage

00:31:19.280 --> 00:31:22.280
would be here, and the
barrier height there.

00:31:22.280 --> 00:31:24.550
And the width of the space
charge region, once again,

00:31:24.550 --> 00:31:26.450
is dependent on
the dopant density

00:31:26.450 --> 00:31:27.890
inside of the semiconductor.

00:31:27.890 --> 00:31:29.920
Here, we've defined it
as Nd, because we're

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:33.050
assuming that this is an n-type
semiconductor with donor atoms.

00:31:33.050 --> 00:31:35.175
But of course, if this were
a p-type semiconductor,

00:31:35.175 --> 00:31:38.360
we'd just replace this with
Na to determine the width.

00:31:38.360 --> 00:31:40.500
And if the dopant
density is small,

00:31:40.500 --> 00:31:42.690
this means that the width
of the space charge region

00:31:42.690 --> 00:31:43.642
is going to be large.

00:31:43.642 --> 00:31:45.100
And that makes
sense, because there

00:31:45.100 --> 00:31:47.210
has to be an equal
amount of charge

00:31:47.210 --> 00:31:48.630
on either side of the junction.

00:31:48.630 --> 00:31:51.910
And if there is less charge
per unit volume here,

00:31:51.910 --> 00:31:54.310
you need a larger volume
to compensate the charge

00:31:54.310 --> 00:31:55.760
on the other side.

00:31:55.760 --> 00:31:59.910
So this is, again, a similar
expression to the one

00:31:59.910 --> 00:32:02.990
that we saw when we were
studying the PN junctions.

00:32:02.990 --> 00:32:05.860
Now, the important
thing to recognize here

00:32:05.860 --> 00:32:09.250
is that, if we have the bands
bending this way, for electrons

00:32:09.250 --> 00:32:12.190
in our system, there may
be a barrier to hop out.

00:32:12.190 --> 00:32:15.010
For holes in the
system, though, this

00:32:15.010 --> 00:32:18.479
could be a favorable
exit strategy,

00:32:18.479 --> 00:32:19.770
if the bands are bent that way.

00:32:19.770 --> 00:32:21.310
If the bends are
bent the other way,

00:32:21.310 --> 00:32:23.640
electrons can rather
easily roll down.

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:27.070
But holes will have a barrier
to go out of the material.

00:32:27.070 --> 00:32:28.790
So the same type
of metal that might

00:32:28.790 --> 00:32:31.620
make an Ohmic contact
for an n-type material

00:32:31.620 --> 00:32:36.510
might make a Schottky contact
for a p-type material.

00:32:36.510 --> 00:32:38.480
Yeah, that's about it.

00:32:38.480 --> 00:32:40.740
So we have to be very careful
in terms of our matching

00:32:40.740 --> 00:32:43.560
or pairing between the
specific type of metal

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:46.870
and the specific
semiconductor involved.

00:32:46.870 --> 00:32:52.400
Let me put that into
perspective here with something

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:54.220
we've already seen.

00:32:54.220 --> 00:32:56.990
Again, the Ohmic contact is one
in which we have a linear IV

00:32:56.990 --> 00:32:57.950
characteristic.

00:32:57.950 --> 00:33:00.310
And the electron barrier
height has to be less than

00:33:00.310 --> 00:33:05.320
or equal to 0, to have the
electrons very easily pop down

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:06.257
into the contact.

00:33:06.257 --> 00:33:07.840
Whereas, for a
Schottky contact, there

00:33:07.840 --> 00:33:09.090
should be some barrier height.

00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:10.190
It should be finite.

00:33:10.190 --> 00:33:13.320
And we should have a difficulty
of moving the electron

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:18.100
from the semiconductor into the
metal, in that particular case.

00:33:18.100 --> 00:33:23.850
So the natural question is,
what metals should we use?

00:33:23.850 --> 00:33:26.020
Or what is the range of
metals that are available?

00:33:26.020 --> 00:33:28.540
If the barrier height is a
function of the work function

00:33:28.540 --> 00:33:30.590
of the metal, what is the
range of work functions

00:33:30.590 --> 00:33:32.260
that are available to us?

00:33:32.260 --> 00:33:35.430
On this green arrow right
here, which is Q times the work

00:33:35.430 --> 00:33:39.180
function of the metal, we have
a range of different metals,

00:33:39.180 --> 00:33:43.010
from aluminum to platinum,
and titanium, zinc, tungsten,

00:33:43.010 --> 00:33:45.219
molybdenum, copper,
nickel, gold, in between.

00:33:45.219 --> 00:33:47.010
And of course, there
are other metals, too,

00:33:47.010 --> 00:33:49.450
in the periodic table that
you can add to this chart.

00:33:49.450 --> 00:33:52.350
But this gives you
a sense of where

00:33:52.350 --> 00:33:54.270
the Fermi energy of
the metal would lie,

00:33:54.270 --> 00:33:56.280
relative to the
vacuum level, and how

00:33:56.280 --> 00:33:59.190
that would match up against
your arbitrary semiconductor.

00:33:59.190 --> 00:34:01.790
This one here happens to be
a silicon carbide material.

00:34:01.790 --> 00:34:04.290
But if you happen to be working
on a different semiconductor

00:34:04.290 --> 00:34:06.790
and place it right here, you
can see where your Fermi energy

00:34:06.790 --> 00:34:09.620
would lie, relative to the
work function of the metal,

00:34:09.620 --> 00:34:11.274
if you line up
the vacuum levels.

00:34:11.274 --> 00:34:12.690
And this gives you
an idea already

00:34:12.690 --> 00:34:16.949
of how the bands
will bend, once you

00:34:16.949 --> 00:34:22.580
adjust the position of the metal
to match up the Fermi energy

00:34:22.580 --> 00:34:24.532
inside of your
semiconductor material.

00:34:24.532 --> 00:34:25.032
Yeah.

00:34:25.032 --> 00:34:28.364
AUDIENCE: So on the left is
an intrinsic semiconductor?

00:34:28.364 --> 00:34:29.320
Is it?

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:30.494
TONIO BUONASSISI: Yeah, it's
pretty close to intrinsic.

00:34:30.494 --> 00:34:31.993
It's a little n-type,
it looks like.

00:34:31.993 --> 00:34:33.650
But it's pretty
close to intrinsic.

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:38.066
This, in this case, just a
variant of silicon carbide.

00:34:38.066 --> 00:34:39.940
There are many polymorphs
of silicon carbide,

00:34:39.940 --> 00:34:44.896
meaning same composition,
same silicon carbon ratio,

00:34:44.896 --> 00:34:46.270
but different
crystal structures,

00:34:46.270 --> 00:34:49.190
depending on how it was grown.

00:34:49.190 --> 00:34:49.691
Yep?

00:34:49.691 --> 00:34:51.606
AUDIENCE: Do you know
where silver would fall?

00:34:51.606 --> 00:34:52.830
TONIO BUONASSISI: Silver?

00:34:52.830 --> 00:34:54.150
AUDIENCE: It's not
listed [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:54.150 --> 00:34:54.840
TONIO BUONASSISI:
No, it's listed.

00:34:54.840 --> 00:34:56.702
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
a lot for [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:56.702 --> 00:34:57.660
TONIO BUONASSISI: Yeah.

00:34:57.660 --> 00:34:59.160
I'm going to have
to guess that it's

00:34:59.160 --> 00:35:01.640
going to fall around here,
just from a similarity

00:35:01.640 --> 00:35:04.110
of other elemental
species in that list.

00:35:04.110 --> 00:35:06.600
Do you happen to remember the
work function of silver, Joe?

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:08.035
Been working with
it a lot lately.

00:35:08.035 --> 00:35:08.534
JOE: Yeah.

00:35:08.534 --> 00:35:09.075
I don't know.

00:35:09.075 --> 00:35:11.200
TONIO BUONASSISI: OK.

00:35:11.200 --> 00:35:12.800
Quick, interesting
aside about silver,

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:14.170
since it was brought up.

